<section class="section section--alt" id="qbo-feat-bank-rules-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What a QuickBooks Online bank rule is, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A bank rule is an instruction you give QuickBooks Online for how to handle transactions the bank feed imports. The feed brings transactions into the <em>For Review</em> queue on the Banking screen; a rule watches that queue and, when a transaction matches the conditions you set, applies the category, payee, and class you chose &mdash; so the routine work of coding recurring charges is already done before you look.</p>
      <p>A rule is built from <em>conditions</em>. You pick whether it applies to money coming in or going out, then add tests on the bank&rsquo;s description text (it <em>contains</em>, or <em>is</em>, certain words) and on the amount (it equals a figure, or falls within a range). You decide whether a transaction has to meet <em>all</em> the conditions or <em>any</em> of them. Rules apply in a <em>priority order</em> from top to bottom, and the first rule that matches a transaction is the one that takes it &mdash; which is why putting specific rules above broad ones matters. A rule can pre-fill the category and leave the transaction in For Review for you to accept, or it can <em>auto-add</em> it straight into the register.</p>
      <p>Rules are the biggest time-saver the feed offers, but it&rsquo;s worth being precise about the risk. A rule applies exactly the logic you gave it &mdash; including any mistake in that logic &mdash; to every transaction that matches, so a careless rule miscategorizes at scale, and an auto-add rule does it silently, with nothing left in For Review to flag it. We describe QuickBooks Online&rsquo;s behavior as it actually works, and we&rsquo;re honest that a rule is a fast default you still verify, not a substitute for reviewing the books.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

